So, there's no way to enter your birthday on startup via the text box. A calendar control comes up when you touch on the field. That calendar control starts at the current month and can ONLY be manipulated by touching a button to go one month earlier. Meaning you have to hit it 12 x 13 (the minimum age to sign up in years) times. It is the single most beautiful instance of webshit garbage I've ever seen in my life. Please never fix it. The app and this bug belong in a museum.

Tips about breathing techniques. 2. Suggesting right posture and some training videos for that. 3. What kind of shoes and other accessory that you should use. 4. Warm up exercises before and after. As of now it only suggests 5 min walk before and after your run. Also, there should be more personalisation within the app. As of now it suggests same plan to everyone. It should not be like that. It should consider user‚Äôs age, capture some physical parameters. On first few days it can ask user to take free run. The training plan that this app delivers is solid- it's a nice gentle buildup that can turn the most ardent couch potato into a runner. That's the good.  The bad:  The server back-end is very unreliable. The app's own syncing is also very buggy- it doesn't ever upload/download your data unless you log out and back in again.  There's no way to set a pre-workout countdown (a la Endomondo). This is really important if you're running with a phone, as you need to hit "start" and then zip it away safely- you always end up missing part of your warmup.  It would also be useful if there was an option to automatically start music with the workout, a minor oversight, but an obvious omission.  If you can put up with these niggles, and follow the training plan (as well as eat/sleep/stretch as you should), you will start feeling fantastic, and find that you can actually run! Automating a decent training plan like this is easily worth the asking price, despite the slightly basic app.

First off, you should know that the app will uninstall itself after the 9 week period, whether you are done with the program or not. I thought that was pretty cheap, when I buy an app I expect to have that app as long as I want it. This app did the basic thing I needed - keeping track of the time intervals - but everything else about it is pretty annoying. Logging workouts to the website required entering userID and pwd everytime, or using FB. The data on pace includes both the warmup/cooldown, so not useful for your actual running pace. GPS is limited to a map only, there is a much better GPS functionality in other apps. The cues for the longer time intervals are basic, just the halfway point. There is no "autopause" function that can tell when you're stopped for whatever reason. There is no way to move to later workouts, you have to "complete" each workout to get to the next one (fortunately, the app is not smart enough to know if you're actually moving, so...)  This comes in handy if you accidentally hit the "quit" button while fumbling for your phone at the end of a workout and delete it. For $2, I guess it's okay, just know that it uninstalls at 9 weeks.
